 - Minimal example in a [Rust Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&amp;mode=debug&amp;edition=2018&amp;gist=033fab2186cf7ca204ad7fa8978489fe)

# Explanation 

I realized that I wished `Index` provided an `enumerate` method to enumerate indices and the items behind the index of the collection. So with the help of the accepted answer https://stackoverflow.com/questions/30630810/using-generic-iterators-instead-of-specific-list-types I implemented a supertrait of `Index` that provides this method.

## Step 1: Define a new `Enumerate` struct and implement `Iterator` for it

```rust
pub struct Enumerate&lt;IndexIter, ItemIter&gt; {
    index: IndexIter,
    item: ItemIter,
}

/// implements the [`Iterator`] trait for the new struct
impl&lt;IndexIter, ItemIter&gt; Iterator for Enumerate&lt;IndexIter, ItemIter&gt;
where
    IndexIter: Iterator,
    ItemIter: Iterator,
{
    type Item = (IndexIter::Item, ItemIter::Item);

    /// returns the next iterator
    #[inline]
    fn next(&amp;mut self) -&gt; Option&lt;(IndexIter::Item, ItemIter::Item)&gt; {
        self.index.next().map(|idx| {
            // CAUTION! We need to make sure that the index and item iterators are ordered consistently.
            // We are really just incrementing two iterators simultaneously here...
            (idx, self.item.next().unwrap())
        })
    }
}
```

## Step 2: Define a supertrait for `Index` that adds the `enumerate` method

```rust
/// trait for implementing over the indices of collections that implement [`std::ops::Index`].
/// 
/// It adds the enumerate function that returns an `Enumerate&lt;IndexIter,ItemIter&gt;` as an iterator.
pub trait SuperIndex&lt;&#39;a, Idx&gt;: std::ops::Index&lt;Idx&gt; {
    type IndexIter: Iterator&lt;Item = Idx&gt;;
    type ItemIter: Iterator;

    /// enumerates over the indices and items of a collection
    fn enumerate(&amp;&#39;a self) -&gt; Enumerate&lt;Self::IndexIter, Self::ItemIter&gt;;
}
```

## Step 3: Implement the supertrait for the collections I want to use

### Implementation for `Vec`
```rust
/// implement the [`SuperIndex`] trait for [`Vec&lt;T&gt;`]
impl&lt;&#39;a, T: &#39;a&gt; SuperIndex&lt;&#39;a, usize&gt; for Vec&lt;T&gt; {
    type IndexIter = std::ops::Range&lt;usize&gt;;
    type ItemIter = std::slice::Iter&lt;&#39;a, T&gt;;

    fn enumerate(&amp;&#39;a self) -&gt; Enumerate&lt;Self::IndexIter, Self::ItemIter&gt; {
        Enumerate {
            index: 0..self.len(),
            item: self.iter(),
        }
    }
}
```

### Implementation for `HashMap`

```rust
/// implement the [`SuperIndex`] trait for [`HashMap&lt;K, V, S&gt;`]
impl&lt;&#39;a, K: &#39;a, V: &#39;a, S&gt; SuperIndex&lt;&#39;a, &amp;&#39;a K&gt; for std::collections::HashMap&lt;K, V, S&gt;
where
    K: Eq + std::hash::Hash,
    S: std::hash::BuildHasher,
{
    type IndexIter = std::collections::hash_map::Keys&lt;&#39;a, K, V&gt;;
    type ItemIter = std::collections::hash_map::Values&lt;&#39;a, K, V&gt;;

    fn enumerate(&amp;&#39;a self) -&gt; Enumerate&lt;Self::IndexIter, Self::ItemIter&gt; {
        Enumerate {
            index: self.keys(),
            item: self.values(),
        }
    }
}
```

# Discussion

Now I can enumerate the index and value for any kind of collection that implements `SuperIndex` and `index` does not have to be a `usize`:

```rust
for (index, item) in c.enumerate() {
    assert_eq!(&amp;c[index], item);
}
```

This implementation does what I want and I can&#39;t think of any alternatives, but it has a few minor pitfalls:

 - `SuperIndex` indices cannot be quite as generic as the ones for `Index`, e.g. slices are not allowed.
 - We need to explicitly implement `SuperIndex` for each collection.
 - In each implementation, we must make sure that the two iterators are ordered consistently.

If there is anything off in my implementation please let me know! It seems to work fine, but I only understand half of what I am doing.

